    },
    {
      "html": "<b>Mrs.\nBernadette </b><b><a name=\"_Toc40905769\">Smith</a></b><b>�(Point\nDouglas):</b> On May&nbsp;7th, to mark national youth mental health day, the\nManitoba Advocate for Children and Youth released their report on the\npersistent gaps in youth mental health and addictions services here in our\nprovince. The report paints a dark picture of the last six years in our\nprovince and the ways that, frankly, we are failing Manitoba's youth�young\npeople. ",
      "index": "00075",
      "speaker": "Bernadette Smith"
    },
    {
      "html": "Rural and northern youth are not met with the services they need in\ntheir own communities. They are asked to travel to Winnipeg, where the demand\nvastly outpaces supply. ",
      "index": "00076",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "The leading cause of death of children in Manitoba aged 11 to 17 is\nsuicide. Manitoba's youth suicides are more than double the national average.\nWe've known this for some time. Yet, nothing seems&nbsp;&nbsp;to have changed.\nWe continue to deal with a hodgepodge of services that the advocate says are\nnot child-friendly nor youth-focused. The VIRGO report told us where and how we\nwere failing back in 2018, and today, very little progress has been made.",
      "index": "00077",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    { "html": "<b>*</b>\n(13:50)", "index": "00078", "speaker": "" },
    {
      "html": "A vast majority of these children are indigenous and we have a\nresponsibility to not only the children, their parents, but to the First Nation\nand the Metis communities to work collaboratively to help keep children\nmentally healthy so that we can eliminate suicides and the deaths of children. ",
      "index": "00079",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� The\nadvocate released her report in the wake of COVID-19 because, and I quote her\nhere�and I'm sure the Premier (Mr. Pallister) should be listening to this: If\nwe've learned anything from the COVID-19 pandemic response it's that\ngovernments are capable of moving quickly on pressing issues. Children cannot\nwait any longer to become the priority of this government. ",
      "index": "00080",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Madam\nSpeaker, this really isn't�there really isn't any excuse here. We have seen how\nquickly things can be done when we see them as urgent, and we've prioritized\nlives and public health. ",
