    {
      "html": "<b>Ms.\nDanielle </b><b><a name=\"_Toc40905808\">Adams</a></b><b>�(Thompson):</b> Just a couple of weeks ago we asked the minister what\nher plan was for child care in Manitoba as we begin to�reopening the economy,\nand two weeks later we have still not heard or seen a plan on how they're\nreopening daycares and how they'll keep workers and kids safe. This is\nconcerning because we know that parent�many parents and businesses can't return\nto work if�safely if their children do not have child care. ",
      "index": "00268",
      "speaker": "Danielle Adams"
    },
    {
      "html": "����� When\nwill the minister release a comprehensive plan for child care that aligns with\nthe economy reopening? ",
      "index": "00269",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<b>Hon.\nHeather </b><b><a name=\"_Toc40905809\">Stefanson</a></b><b>�(Minister of Families):</b> We've been working closely with the\nManitoba Child Care Association, with early childhood educators, with parents,\nMadam Speaker, parents who are looking to find child-care facilities that are\nopen and matching them and we have been quite successful in doing so. We have\nover 500 facilities that are open in the province of Manitoba. We have just\nunder 900&nbsp;vacancies within that. By the end of this month we'll have more\nthan 275 more child-care facilities opening up. ",
      "index": "00270",
      "speaker": "Heather Stefanson"
    },
    {
      "html": "����� There's\nmore work to be done, Madam Speaker. We'll continue to work with parents and\nchildhood educators to ensure that child care is there for parents when they\nneed it. ",
      "index": "00271",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<b>Madam\nSpeaker:</b> The honourable member for Thompson, on a supplementary question. ",
      "index": "00272",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<b>Ms.\nAdams:</b> The minister claims she wants to open 6,000 homes to child care, but\nwe know that this was a failure as we continue to hear from families\nacross�that child-care services is needed. We simply don't have the child-care\ncapacity right now to meet the demands of Manitobans returning to work because\nthe minister has spent more time focusing on this failed plan than providing a\nreal plan. ",
      "index": "00273",
      "speaker": "Danielle Adams"
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Child care is essential. The Premier (Mr. Pallister) and this\ngovernment should make it a priority. ",
      "index": "00274",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� How\nmuch of the $18 million devoted to home child care has been spent to date? ",
      "index": "00275",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<b>Mrs.\nStefanson:</b> As a result of that program we've been able to open up more than\n100 new child-care spaces in the province of Manitoba. I hardly think that\nthat's irrelevant for those parents that need to access child care in our\nprovince. ",
      "index": "00276",
      "speaker": "Heather Stefanson"
    },
    {
      "html": "����� So,\nagain, we'll continue to work with parents. We'll continue to work with\nstakeholders to ensure that child care is there for parents when they need it,\nespecially as they start to move back towards employment, going back to work in\nthe province of Manitoba. We'll make sure that child care is there for them\nwhen they need it. ",
      "index": "00277",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<b>Madam\nSpeaker:</b> The honourable member for Thompson, on a final supplementary.",
      "index": "00278",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<b>Ms.\nAdams:</b> This is million dollars in funding that could have been put towards\nfront-line child-care centres to pay for protective�personal protective\nequipment and aid in their reopening. So without a plan and without proper\nfunding no economy recovery plan will be successful. ",
      "index": "00279",
      "speaker": "Danielle Adams"
    },
    {
      "html": "����� We need a real investment in publicly funded, accessible and\naffordable child care. We need a plan that shows we actually believe child care\nis essential. ",
      "index": "00280",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Will\nthe minister redirect the funds and produce a comprehensive plan for child care\nimmediately? ",
      "index": "00281",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<b>Mrs.\nStefanson:</b> Well, as a result of 17 years of NDP mismanagement in the area\nof child care, where they took a very ideological approach to child care\ndelivery in the province of Manitoba, Madam Speaker, I will tell you that we\ntake a very different approach. ",
      "index": "00282",
      "speaker": "Heather Stefanson"
    },
    {
      "html": "����� We\nwant to ensure that child care is there for Manitoba families when they need\nit. We will develop a system and a program that is there for those families\nwhen they need it, because that is what child care should provide in the\nprovince of Manitoba. ",
      "index": "00283",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<b>Madam\nSpeaker:</b> The time for oral questions has expired. ",
      "index": "00284",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<b>Madam\nSpeaker:</b><a name=\"_Toc40905811\"></a> And I have a ruling for the House.",
      "index": "00285",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Immediately following the prayer on March&nbsp;&nbsp;11th,&nbsp;2020,\nthe honourable Leader of the Official Opposition (Mr. Kinew) raised a matter of\nprivilege contending that the government was violating his privileges and the\nprivileges of all Manitobans by having a large number of government bills\nplaced on the notice and order papers. He stated that this was undermining\ndemocratic processes and was intended to supress debate and discussion. ",
      "index": "00286",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� At the conclusion of his remarks he moved that, and I quote: that\nthe issue of the Pallister's government abuse of the rules of this House and\nits undemocratic practices be immediately referred to a committee of the House.\nEnd quote. ",
      "index": "00287",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� The\nhonourable Government House Leader (Mr.&nbsp;Goertzen) and the honourable\nmember for River Heights (Mr. Gerrard) also spoke to the matter of privilege,\nwhich was then taken under advisement.",
      "index": "00288",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� I thank all honourable members for their advice to the Chair.",
      "index": "00289",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� There are two conditions that must be satisfied in order for the\nmatter raised to be ruled in order as a prima facie case of privilege. First,\nwas the issue raised at the earliest opportunity, and second, has sufficient\nevidence been provided to demonstrate that the privileges of the House have\nbeen breeched in order to warrant putting the matter to the House.",
      "index": "00290",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� On the first issue of timeliness the honourable Leader of the\nOfficial Opposition (Mr. Kinew) advised that he was raising the issue at the\nearliest opportunity on Wednesday, March 11th. However, the government bills he\nwas referring to appeared on the Notice Paper on Tuesday, March 10th. Therefore,\nI conclude that the issue of timeliness was not met. ",
      "index": "00291",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Regarding the second issue, I would like to advise the House that a\nmatter concerning the methods by which the House proceeds in the conduct of\nbusiness is a matter of order, not privilege. Joseph Maingot, in the second\nedition of Parliamentary Privilege in Canada, states on page 14 that, and I\nquote, allegations of breech of privilege by a member in the House that amount\nto complaints about procedures and practices in the House are, by very nature,\nmatters of order. End quote. ",
      "index": "00292",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� He also states, on page 223 of the same edition, and I quote, a\nbreech of the standing orders or a failure to follow an established practice\nwould invoke a point of order rather than a question of privilege. End quote.",
      "index": "00293",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� I should also note that the protection of parliamentary privilege\nonly applies to members of the Legislative Assembly and is not applicable to\nthe public. ",
      "index": "00294",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Although the honourable Leader of the Official Opposition may have\na difference of opinion regarding the timing of and volume of government\nlegislation coming forward it falls more into a category of a complaint against\nthe government, and nor has it been demonstrated that a breach of parliamentary\nprivilege has occurred. ",
      "index": "00295",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� With\nthe greatest of respect I therefore rule that the matter raised does not\nfulfill the criteria of a prima facie case of privilege.� ",
      "index": "00296",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
