    {
      "html": "<b>Madam Speaker:</b> Before recognizing the honourable member for St.\nBoniface, I should remind all members that under rule 32�38(2), the mover of a\nmotion on a matter of urgent public importance and one member from the other\nrecognized parties in the House are allowed not more than 10 minutes to explain\nthe urgency of debating the matter immediately. ",
      "index": "00364",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� As\nstated in Beauchesne's, citation 390, urgency in this context means the urgency\nof immediate debate, not of the subject matter of the motion. In their&nbsp;&nbsp;remarks,\nmembers should focus exclusively on whether or not there is urgency of debate\nand whether or not the ordinary opportunities for debate will enable the House\nto consider the matter early enough to ensure that the public interest will not\nsuffer. ",
      "index": "00365",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<b>Mr. Lamont:</b> I do hope that we can have an urgent public debate on\nthe hiring of David McLaughlin in&nbsp;&nbsp;the position of the Clerk of the\nExecutive Council. It is important in that it is an unprecedented\npoliticization of the public service. ",
      "index": "00366",
      "speaker": "Dougald Lamont"
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Because we are in a pandemic and because there are special rules\naround our sitting, this is our first opportunity to address this issue since\nit was announced last week. Clearly, we will not have any other opportunities\nto discuss this in the House in the next days until the next week. ",
      "index": "00367",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� I would add there are a number of standard objections to raising\nthese issues, namely that there are often other venues and opportunities to\nraise this issue, but the current situation of the emergency and special\nsittings�and special arrangements we've had to make around this�means that\nthose opportunities are not available to us. ",
