    },
    {
      "html": "����� If MASC is not working well and quickly when farmers need their\nhelp, it is a big problem. We do not need and do not want the Manitoba\nAgricultural Services Corporation to be 'e-MASC-ulated'. Add to this today's\nfarmers are seeding and very soon the crops will be growing. We hope there are\nnot major problems with hail this year, but if there are MASC will be needed,\nand there can be a big demand on MASC services if it is a bad hail year. This\nis not the time for cutbacks on MASC services. ",
      "index": "00441",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Second, MASC has an outstanding record of performance and achievement\nand service to farmers. I have talked to many farmers, and it is rare to find a&nbsp;&nbsp;farmer\nwho is not thankful for what used to be crop insurance and is now a MASC\nAgriInsurance program. Indeed, I've been told by one long-time farmer that the\nMASC programs are the most important programs for farmers. In a tribute to\nMASC,&nbsp;&nbsp;one farmer told me, talking to me on his cell phone as he was\nseeding this morning, that he has not met even one farmer who has hesitated to\nput in a crop this year, even with all the uncertainty about the COVID-19\nsituation. Farmers are not hesitating because they know MASC is there for them.\n",
      "index": "00442",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� That is one of the biggest tributes I can say in support of MASC.\nMASC has essentially been the insurer, the securer of our home-grown food\nsupply, and the food supply from Manitoba which is exported around the world\nand which is so important to people all over the world. ",
      "index": "00443",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� I say to the Premier (Mr. Pallister): Do not let Manitoba farmers\ndown by cutting back on MASC. It is working well. Farmers tell me they do not\nsee any frills in MASC. MASC is already a lean operation. In my experience, if\nyou have a program with a really good track record and which is running well,\ndon't mess with it and cause problems which we don't need. Programs like MASC\nare an example of how a helpful government program can be run to help farmers. ",
      "index": "00444",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Third, MASC is a lean program and is constantly improving its\nprograms and services and using more digital delivery of services. It does not\nmake sense to arbitrarily cut a lean and efficiently run service. A number of\nyears ago, there was a technology switch at MASC so that adjusters were working\nwith laptop computers and MASC did not cut back on the number of�did cut back,\nthen, on the number of employees who were keying in data because they weren't\nneeded as much anymore. There was a business case then for cutbacks and they\nwere made. There is no business case now for cutbacks to MASC. ",
      "index": "00445",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Fourth, MASC is currently in the middle of a technology\ntransformation. It is a massive job. The government should not be cutting back\nstaff at MASC in the middle of this transformation. It involves a lot of extra\ntraining. It involves major adjustments to the work, and this is not a time to\nbe cutting people when the people are badly needed by and for the organization\nand for farmers. ",
      "index": "00446",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Fifth, most MASC programs are run with a combination of federal and\nprovincial dollars. It is important that Manitoba is able to deliver programs\nlike AgriStability and AgriInsurance well on behalf of both governments. ",
      "index": "00447",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� I say to the Premier: Please do not put us in a position where\nfarmers have trouble accessing federal as well as provincial programs. ",
      "index": "00448",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Sixth, we are in the middle of a pandemic. Now is not the time to\nbe cutting staff and destabilizing people's lives. Indeed, MASC is needed at\nfull strength right now not just to deal with the backlog, not just to deal\nwith a technology transformation, but specifically because there is added need\nfor flexibility in the response to the pandemic. People at MASC have adjusted\nwith more people working from home, <span lang=\"EN-US\">although adjusting and\nlending staff are still going out to meet farmers while following full physical\ndistancing guidelines. </span>",
      "index": "00449",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    { "html": "<b>*</b>\n(15:20)", "index": "00450", "speaker": "" },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� The Cabinet may want to run a new program through\nMASC to help farmers manage the difficult situation, for example, with falling\nbeef prices. Flexibility and rapidity of response are critical during&nbsp;&nbsp;the\nCOVID-19 pandemic. You do not want to&nbsp;&nbsp;cut the very people who are so\ncritical in helping&nbsp;&nbsp;with the pandemic response. I say to the\nPremier: do not cut the people who are so essential to farmers producing our\nfood supply during this COVID-19 pandemic. </span>",
      "index": "00451",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� Madam Speaker, I talked to one farmer who had this\nto say: he said he had heard that the Premier was calling for MASC to make\ncutbacks. He said: I would be hard pressed to see where the Premier's coming\nfrom. He added: I'm not sure what message the Premier and his government are\nsending by making cutbacks to MASC, but I, as a farmer, don't like the\nmessage.� </span>",
      "index": "00452",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� Madam Speaker, I speak today on this critical\nmatter, the future of MASC and the critical need for&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;MASC, the\nManitoba Agricultural Service Corporation, to be fully staffed and fully\noperational at this most critical of years for all of us. </span>",
      "index": "00453",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� I ask the Premier: Does he really want to be known\nfrom now on by farmers and by Manitobans as the chief 'e-MASC-ulator'? </span>",
      "index": "00454",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� Second, I will speak briefly on the children's\nspecial allowances. The provincial government is grabbing money from\nchildren�children who are the most vulnerable in our society in CFS care�and\nthey're using legislation which they're bringing in in this session to make it\nvery difficult for the children to ever get their money back. This is wrong. </span>",
      "index": "00455",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� Third, I will say a few words about Manitoba\nHydro. The Premier is mandating major cutbacks in the number of employees at\nManitoba Hydro. Manitoba Hydro has, over many years, provided excellent service\nto Manitobans. All over our province, Manitobans rely on having access to\nManitoba Hydro's electricity. The safety and security of our Hydro network in\nManitoba is critically important to all of us. </span>",
      "index": "00456",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� With our cold winters, we cannot tolerate delays\nin restoring power. Manitoba farmers, as an example, are very dependent on\nManitoba Hydro for their home and their farming operations. Food processors and\nother manufacturers, as with virtually every business in our province, is\ndependent on Manitoba Hydro. </span>",
      "index": "00457",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� Why is the Premier putting the access to\nManitoba's�Hydro's�electricity at risk? Why, at the time of the COVID-19\npandemic, is the Premier acting to put at risk the basic lives, businesses and\nsecurity of Manitobans by making cutbacks to Manitoba Hydro? Why, at a time\nwhen we're moving toward more use of renewable electricity, including\nhydroelectric power, would the Premier and his government jeopardize the future\nof Manitoba Hydro? </span>",
      "index": "00458",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� Manitoba Hydro workers contribute much to our\nprovince. The Province should not desert Hydro employees at the time of this\npandemic. </span>",
      "index": "00459",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� Already, the Premier has made deep cuts to\nManitoba Hydro. For the first time in my more than 20 years as an MLA, I have\nreceived repeated concerns about electricity outages in a part of River\nHeights. It is likely the slower response and the repeated nature of the\noutages are a result of the cutbacks the Premier has already made. </span>",
      "index": "00460",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� The Premier should not make further cuts, as he's\nnow doing. He will jeopardize the security we all have from a high-performing\nutility. I call on the Premier to act immediately to abandon his cuts to\nManitoba Hydro. </span>",
      "index": "00461",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� Merci. Miigwech. Thank you. </span>",
      "index": "00462",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<b>Madam Speaker:</b> <span lang=\"EN-US\">The House\nwill now consider the opposition day motion of the honourable Leader of the\nOfficial Opposition. </span>",
      "index": "00463",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� I will now recognize the honourable Leader of the Official\nOpposition. </span>",
      "index": "00464",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<b>Mr. Wab </b><b><a name=\"_Toc40905830\">Kinew</a></b><b>�(Leader of the Official Opposition):</b> I move,\nseconded by the member for Fort Garry (Mr. Wasyliw), that pursuant to section&nbsp;27(1)\nof The Public Utilities Board Act, the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba\nrequests that the Public Utilities Board immediately hold an extraordinary\nhearing into the proposed $86 million in&nbsp;&nbsp;cuts from Manitoba Hydro's\noperations and workforce, including up to 700 layoffs that have been directed\nby the provincial government; and further requests the provincial government's\ndirective be suspended until the PUB's hearing has taken place. ",
      "index": "00465",
      "speaker": "Wab Kinew"
    },
    {
      "html": "<b><i>Motion\npresented.</i></b> ",
      "index": "00466",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<b>Mr. Kinew:</b> The motion before the House today gives this government\na simple choice: Will they be open and transparent, or will they continue to\nrun away and hide from accountability? ",
      "index": "00467",
      "speaker": "Wab Kinew"
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Since the announcement that this government is obsessed with laying\noff Manitobans in the public sector took particular shape in the form of a\ndirective to put 700 Manitoba Hydro employees out of work, we have been\nstanding up for Manitobans' jobs. We have been working very hard to ensure that\nthe government face accountability, face public pressure and eventually back\noff their plan to put all these Manitobans out of work. ",
      "index": "00468",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� We know economic history and theory teaches us that during a\nrecession governments have to make investments to keep Manitobans working and\nto keep the economy moving. What I just said, Madam Speaker, was a paraphrase\nof what former Prime Minister Stephen Harper said in 2008 during the great\nfinancial crisis.� ",
      "index": "00469",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� So it is clear from his actions, if perhaps not his words, that the\nissue of putting people out of work during a recession being a terrible idea is\nagreed by both those on the right wing as well as on the left wing. It simply\ndefies logic and common sense that this government, seeing so many sectors of\nthe economy hurting right now, would decide that the appropriate response is to\ngo to some of those sectors still operating and decide to cause economic pain\nand misery there as well. It will not only prolong the recession and deepen the\ncurrent economic crisis�when we look at the role of Manitoba Hydro in our\nprovince's economy in terms of its future for the environment and in terms of\nreconciliation with impacts on indigenous communities, we know that the cut\nbeing handed down under the cover of the COVID pandemic will be one that\nManitobans pay the price for for many, many years to come. ",
      "index": "00470",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� And so\nthe motion that we move today accomplishes the following, Madam Speaker: it\nwould ask the Public Utilities Board, according to a section of the act that\ngoverns them, to have a hearing to investigate the facts surrounding this cut\nof Manitoba Hydro that has been ordered by this government. ",
      "index": "00471",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<i>Mr. Doyle Piwniuk, Deputy Speaker, in the Chair</i> ",
      "index": "00472",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Now, the Public Utilities Board has actually been quite helpful for\nus in this respect. Last week, I took the opportunity to write a letter to the\nPUB to ask them to commence such a hearing. Now, on the first day the PUB's\nresponse initially was to say that they didn't have the power to compel the\ngovernment��or to order the government to do something. Now, this was important\nbecause up to now the minister and the Premier (Mr. Pallister) have previously\ntried to avoid taking responsibility for the cuts taking place at Manitoba\nHydro, though clearly, the chair of the Public Utilities Board is connecting\nthe dots and saying that these cuts are the direction of this government. ",
      "index": "00473",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� But their helpfulness went even beyond that. Just today we received\na letter from the Public Utilities Board which made clear that the PUB could\ncommence this hearing that we're asking for should they be asked to do so by a\nresolution passed in this Legislature. Of course, this letter also said that\nthe PUB will be investigating this matter at their next hearing. ",
      "index": "00474",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    { "html": "<b>*</b> (15:30)", "index": "00475", "speaker": "" },
    {
      "html": "����� So, again, just to make it plain, the PUB will, at the next\nhearing, investigate how damaging these 700 job cuts at Manitoba Hydro are and\nhow damaging to our overall economic, environmental and social future this\n$86-million cut that this government has ordered will be to Manitoba in the\nlong term.",
      "index": "00476",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� So this is a series of questions that will be asked of the\ngovernment. There will be a truth ascertained at the end of this process. The\nquestion for the government today is will they delay and will they wait for\nthat Public Utilities Board hearing to happen some time, perhaps, later this\nyear when there's another rate review application, or will the government avail\nitself of the motion before them today and agree to subject themselves to the\nopen and honest accountability questions that Manitobans want asked.",
      "index": "00477",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Now, we know that there are many Manitobans out there who do not\nunderstand why this government is so obsessed with putting working people out\nof work in this province. But, when it comes to Manitoba Hydro, we know that\nthere is a few key issues that come to mind for the average person. Many, many\npeople, since the 700 layoffs were announced by this government, have asked the\nquestion about why would the government cut jobs at Hydro when we just recently\nhad the experience of that terrible snowstorm last October. ",
      "index": "00478",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Many people in Portage la Prairie, surrounding region, in the\nInterlake and other parts of Manitoba were without power for an extended period\nof time. There were many people who banded together, luckily, and were able to\nget some assistance from Hydro and from the workers from other utilities after\na number of hours and, in some cases, days. However, that showed us that, in\nthis period of climate change where great storms occur with increasing\nfrequency, the importance of having front-line workers at our public\nhydroelectric utility available to spring into action, to serve the needs of\nthe people of Manitoba. And yet, so many people hear about the 700 job cuts,\nand they ask, well, how quickly are we going to be able to respond to the next storm.\nAnd that's a legitimate question. And it is one that should rightly be referred\nto the Public Utilities Board today by having the government members vote in\nfavour of this motion.",
      "index": "00479",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� I would also point out it was not lost on many of these people\nasking the same question that members on the other side of the House last fall\nwere quick to say thank you, Manitoba Hydro workers, and they stood and they\nclapped for the workers when they stood in the gallery on that side of the\nChamber, Mr.&nbsp;Speaker. And yet those same workers that they professed to\nhave admiration for and gratitude towards last fall are the very same workers\nthat they now aim to put out of work during a pandemic and economic crisis no\nless.",
      "index": "00480",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Now, beyond that, we know that the importance of Manitoba Hydro is\nquite far reaching to the future of our province. If we are to be able to\nreduce emissions of greenhouse gases in the long term, we need to be able to\ntransition away from carbon-intensive fuels to using renewable forms of\nelectricity. Manitoba Hydro is well positioned to play a very important role in\ndoing that. ",
      "index": "00481",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� We also know that in terms of economic development, Manitoba\nHydro's importance as a job creator, as an engine of growth, is quite important\nthere, as well.",
      "index": "00482",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� And, finally, we know that in spite of the positive contributions\nthat Manitoba Hydro has made over the years to the�to our province, there has\nalso been a terrible human toll that has been visited primarily on indigenous\npeople within Manitoba. And so, while Manitoba Hydro, on the one hand, looks to\nthe future to drive a clean, green economic growth-oriented exercise of its\nmission here in the province, at the same time, we must expect that it also\nadvance the mission of reconciling with its impact on indigenous communities and\nothers across northern Manitoba. And yet, if this utility is cut further by\nthis government, all of those goals, important as they are to our society, to\nour province and to our economic recovery, will be put into a weakened\nposition. They will be slowed down, and, indeed, in some cases, as we're\nseeing, they will actually be moved backwards. ",
      "index": "00483",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� And so our concern here is that the actions of this government will\nweaken one of our most important Crown corporations, our most important public\nutility, probably setting the stage for privatization on the part of this\ngovernment, but will eventually lead to weakened quality of service, will lead\nto slower response times and, of course, will lead to longer waits for\nManitobans who are looking to get the construction industry back on its feet.\nAll those measures taken together will prolong the economic misery and will\ndamage our economic recovery. ",
      "index": "00484",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� We're\ncomfortable bringing these facts to the Public Utilities Board. I suggest that\nthe government get on board, subject itself to accountability and agree to have\nthis hearing at the PUB today. ",
      "index": "00485",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<b>Mr.\nAdrien </b><b><a name=\"_Toc40905831\">Sala</a></b><b>�(St. James):</b> Proud to stand and speak to our motion here today,\nwhich requests that the Public Utilities Board hold an extraordinary hearing\ninto the impacts of the $87 million in cuts to Manitoba Hydro which have been\nproposed by this government. ",
      "index": "00486",
      "speaker": "Adrien Sala"
    },
    {
      "html": "����� As was just stated, this is really about trans-parency versus\nsecrecy, Mr. Deputy Speaker. We have real concerns about the goals of this\ngovernment in making these cuts, and it is only reasonable that we can look to\nthe Public Utilities Board to help to ensure that these cuts will not have a\nprolonged or significant amount of�create a significant amount of damage to our\npublicly owned utility and the Crown jewel here in Manitoba�Manitoba Hydro.",
      "index": "00487",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� In the midst of a pandemic, the government is attempting to move\nforward with an egregious attack on Manitoba Hydro, and that's bound to\ncompromise the integrity of their services and it's bound to create real safety\nrisks to Manitoba Hydro workers and the public at a time when we need energy\nsecurity more than ever. ",
      "index": "00488",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� The fact is this government is willing to lay off 700 Hydro workers\nin the middle of a pandemic after Manitoba Hydro's own executive stated with\ntotal clarity that any job cuts above and beyond the 900 cuts which took place\nat this government's direction over the last few years�it demonstrates a\nreckless disregard for the wellbeing and safety of Hydro employees as well as\nthe financial security of these Manitoban families. It's shameful and, frankly,\nit's bad governance.� ",
      "index": "00489",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� It may be worth reviewing the realities faced by Manitoba Hydro\nemployees on a daily basis to inform the government why these cuts are so\nincredibly reckless and why they present a genuine threat to the safety of\nManitobans. ",
      "index": "00490",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Mr. Deputy Speaker, Hydro employees are constantly exposed to the\nserious hazards on the job, such as high pressure natural gas and high voltage\nelectricity, and I don't have to tell you that both of these energy sources can\nbe very unforgiving and that even the slightest mistake on the job can be\nfatal. ",
      "index": "00491",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� With these job cuts, which are being made after this government\nalready shrunk Hydro's workforce by 18 per cent, many Hydro employees will have\nno choice but to cut corners in their work to save time, or they will have to\ncomplete jobs with one employee where there should be two employees simply\nbecause there will be a lack of trained employees available. ",
      "index": "00492",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� I repeat, Mr.\nDeputy Speaker, we are creating a situation where Manitoba Hydro employees are\ngoing to be forced to cut corners because they've already experienced and\nendured 900 job cuts over the last handful of years and now they're being asked\nto proceed with another 700 job cuts or 700 layoffs that will ensure that\nManitoba Hydro employees working in the field are going to face much greater\nrisks because they simply won't be able to have the security of having a second\nemployee to perform a job where they need to, and instead they're going to be\nneeding to proceed with one. Or, they'll find themselves in a situation where a\njob needs to be done, and they'll be forced to cut corners in order to get that\npiece of work done because they're working for Manitobans and they want to\nensure that we can continue to proceed and receive the energy security we all\ndeserve.",
      "index": "00493",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Mr. Deputy\nSpeaker, it's basic logic that these cuts are going to create a significant\nincrease in the level of safety risks faced by large numbers of Hydro\nemployees, and for what? All for the purpose of saving a marginal sum in the\nmidst of a pandemic, and this at a time when we should be investing in the\nManitoban economy. ",
      "index": "00494",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    { "html": "<b>*</b> (15:40)", "index": "00495", "speaker": "" },
    {
      "html": "����� Mr. Deputy\nSpeaker, we know�we've heard from all corners of Manitoba, from opinion makers\non the left and on the right, that this is a time not to be making huge cuts to\nour budget, but it's in fact a time to be investing in the Manitoban economy.\nAnd instead, this government is proceeding with these reckless cuts, which not\nonly are going to create safety risks for Manitoba Hydro works,\nwhich�workers�not only going to create safety risks for Manitobans, but they're\nalso bound to further prolong the amount of time that it will take for this\neconomy to recover. ",
      "index": "00496",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� This is\ntotally and completely inacceptable, and it suggests that this government has a\ndisregard for the safety of our employees at our most important Crown\ncorporation. ",
      "index": "00497",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� You know, the\ngovernment may think that cuts to&nbsp;&nbsp;administrative employees at Hydro\nare acceptable, but we know that cuts to administrative supports are&nbsp;&nbsp;no\nless impactful than cuts to employees who are&nbsp;&nbsp;working in the field.\nIt's those administrative employees that ensure that workers out in the field\nget access to their protective equipment that ensures that those workers in the\nfield have the required supports they need in the back office to do their job\nsafely. ",
      "index": "00498",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� So I repeat,\ncuts to administrative employees are no less damaging or impactful than cuts to\nemployees in the field, in terms of endangering the safety of Manitoba Hydro\nworkers as well as regular Manitobans. It's a reckless move and it creates\nfurther risks for Manitoban�Manitoba Hydro employees working in the field. ",
      "index": "00499",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Mr. Deputy\nSpeaker, every single day almost every single person in this Chamber relies on\nelectricity and natural gas to meet our personal needs and the needs of our\nfamilies. And yet, in the midst of a pandemic, the importance of safe and\nsecure energy services could not be greater. How is it even possible that this\ngovernment is willing to attack and layoff these very same people who are\nproviding each and every one of us with an essential service every day here? ",
      "index": "00500",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� It's patently\nirresponsible, and it demonstrates a lack of respect for the Manitobans who are\nworking to provide us with these services. The government's proceeding with\nthese job cuts while at the same time, they're paying $2.5 million for a sham\nreview led by two ex-Conservative premiers. ",
      "index": "00501",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� That's an insult, Mr. Deputy\nSpeaker, to Manitoba Hydro employees that they're facing layoffs at the same\ntime as this government is paying their Conservative friends to study projects\nwhich were already reviewed in depth�",
      "index": "00502",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<b>Mr. Deputy\nSpeaker:</b> Order. Order. ",
      "index": "00503",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� I just want to remind the member\nfrom St. James that because it's under advisement to the Speaker of�the\ncompensation, I request that we restrain from talking about that topic. ",
      "index": "00504",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<b>Mr. Sala:</b> None of these cuts make\nsense, Mr. Deputy Speaker, and yet� ",
      "index": "00505",
      "speaker": "Adrien Sala"
    },
    {
      "html": "<b>Mr. Deputy Speaker:</b> The\nhonourable member for St. Johns, on a point of order. ",
      "index": "00506",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    { "html": "<b>Point of Order</b>", "index": "00507", "speaker": "" },
    {
      "html": "<b>Ms. Nahanni Fontaine (Official\nOpposition House Leader):</b> Deputy Speaker, could you please clarify what you\njust decreed to the member for St. James (Mr. Sala)? ",
      "index": "00508",
      "speaker": "Nahanni Fontaine"
    },
    {
