    {
      "html": "<b>Mrs. Smith:</b> I apologize for that. ",
      "index": "00659",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� I am shocked�oh, to meet the Premier's demands for cutbacks, Hydro\nhas said it will need to lay off 700&nbsp;people or 13 per cent of the\nworkforce. There are reports that even if public entities find other ways to\nprovide the savings demanded by the Premier from now until the fall, they must\nstill make workforce reductions. ",
      "index": "00660",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� There is no downturn in demand for Hydro, Madam Speaker, meaning\nthat layoffs are not justified or sustainable. This is outrageous. ",
      "index": "00661",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "����� Why does the Premier want to punish the average person? Over 84,000\nManitobans are out of work or underemployed. The government can't directly do\nmuch more�do much about many of the job losses but it can support public sector\njobs. It makes no sense to take from Hydro workers to re-allocate for COVID\nresponse or recovery. This will just hurt people and our chances for a speedy\nrecovery. The provincial government is doing some of the right things, <span lang=\"EN-US\">such as investing in subsidies and programs to fill gaps left by\nfederal benefits, but these efforts are reversed by the Premier's austerity\nprograms cut to community groups and outright attacks on the public sector. </span>",
      "index": "00662",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    { "html": "<b>*</b>\n(16:40)", "index": "00663", "speaker": "" },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� Hydro is deemed an essential service and we are\nall relying on our public energy to get through this pandemic. Many people who\nhave been able to keep working are doing so from home and need reliable,\naffordable energy. Businesses and industries that have stayed open or are\nslowly reopening are relying on Hydro to be there when they need it.</span>",
      "index": "00664",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� Hydro should not have to wait one more minute\ntrying to deliver these ill-conceived job cuts. Hydro has gone through a lot\nunder this government, so much that many people are wondering if the government\nvalues are safe, reliable, affordable public energy at all. </span>",
      "index": "00665",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� I have these additional reasons for opposing job\ncuts at Hydro. Manitoba Hydro work has not diminished. It is always increasing.\nHydro continues to hire contractors, claiming it has insufficient human\nresources to accomplish the work that it needs to do. Unlike other businesses,\neveryone has been doing work, has been working during the COVID-19 pandemic. </span>",
      "index": "00666",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� Other layoffs came as a result of decreased\nbusiness. The way to fight off unemployment in other sectors is not to add to\nthe unemployment rolls by laying off fully employed workers at a successful\ncorporation. Economics�'econominics'�economics from all over have noted that\nManitoba's economy is in a precarious position and needs to be bolstered, not&nbsp;fully\nhampered�further hampered. An additional 700 unemployed will further reduce\nspending, reinvestment in the economy while taking away resources from those\nwho are truly in need, though�or through no fault of their own.</span>",
      "index": "00667",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� The Premier (Mr. Pallister) has yet to give any\nconcrete supportable evidence that Manitoba Hydro has suffered decreased\neconomic activity. If this is a true case, why will he not substantiate his\nclaims by providing irrefutable proof? His statement, and I quote: I think\nreality is Hydro provides many services to the public sector that it does not\nto provide to such a degree right now because the private sector in Manitoba is\ndysfunctional. End of quote. Has not been corroborated by either Manitoba Hydro\nor the government. </span>",
      "index": "00668",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� Manitoba Hydro reduced its staffing levels by 18&nbsp;per\ncent in 2017. By its own admission�this is Bruce Owen's quote, who's a Hydro\nspokesperson�and he stated on May 1st, 2019, that the corporation believed, and\nI quote: That further staff reductions would significantly increase the risk of\npublic and employee safety, of system reliability and, as well, as our ability\nto provide reasonable levels of service to our customers.</span>",
      "index": "00669",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� �Today, one year later, the same utility that's\nmanaged to keep pace with just the 'miminum' number of employees is suddenly\ncapable of reducing its staff complement by another 11 per cent? Taking Hydro\nat its word, it will be impossible to maintain safety, reliability and service\nto Manitobans. Please let me know what you are doing to stop job cuts at Hydro\nand of other public entities. </span>",
      "index": "00670",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� Yours truly, Jennifer Lidgett.� </span>",
      "index": "00671",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� And I'm going to table this.</span>",
      "index": "00672",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� So, again, another Manitoban who is not supportive\nof this government cutting services to Manitobans, services that Manitobans\nneed. If there's another snowstorm, if there's another natural disaster where\nwe need Hydro workers to come out, where are these Hydro workers going to come\nfrom? </span>",
      "index": "00673",
      "speaker": ""
    },
    {
      "html": "<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� So I implore this government to support this\nopposition motion and call a hearing into the proposed $87 million in cuts to\nManitoba Hydro. </span>",
